    {
      "id": 541183,
      "category": "researcher",
      "content": "When importing a project from Github (dotcom or GHES) server, Gitlab uses Octokit to fetch necessary infos (repo, contributors, pull requests, notes,...).\n\nUnder the hood, Octokit uses [Sawyer](https://github.com/lostisland/sawyer) as its hypermedia agent. Github API requests will return ```Sawyer::Resource``` objects. A  ```Sawyer::Resource``` object is placeholder of around 10 nested Ruby objects (most of them are Ruby Hash objects). **Parsing a 1MB data (response) into ```Sawyer::Resource``` objects results in allocating 250MB memory.** Parsing some responses concurrently would cause OOM-killed to the Puma main process --> knocking down Gitlab web services. It takes around 2 minutes for the Puma main process and all workers to restart.\n\nThis is my first H1 report. I'd like to express my sincere gratitude to @h1_analyst_indy and @gmyers for your patience while dealing with me and my (many) wrong assumptions :v\n\nAlso thanks @ammar2 for below blog post about an issue that \"allowed anyone to send certain malformed packets and crash a MineCraft server by running it out of memory\". \nhttps://blog.ammaraskar.com/minecraft-vulnerability-advisory/",
      "updated_at": "2026-01-31T06:48:29.237Z",
